posts.title: Community-owned Westmill solar park appoints management company
posts.text:
Community-owned Westmill solar park appoints management company Pete Hughes @OxMailPeteH Environment reporter covering South Oxford, Kennington & Wantage. Call me on 01865 425431 Visitors get a guided tour of Westmill Solar Park in 2014. Picture: Damian Halliwell 0 comments 
A COMMUNITY-owned solar farm in Oxfordshire which was the largest in the UK when it opened is to be managed by a private company. 
Westmill Solar Park's owners have appointed one of the UK's biggest solar management companies, BSR, to run the facility. 
The firm will manage the park on behalf of its more-than 1,500 co-operative investor owners. 
Westmill, near Watchfield, was the first community-owned solar park in the UK and the world’s largest when it launched in 2012. 
The co-op chose BSR to manage the 5MW project following a competitive tender, and the contract began this month, when BSR said it 'initiated a review of the plant to optimise performance'. 
Westmill Solar Co-operative director Martin Allman said: "We are delighted to have BSR working with us to maintain the excellent performance of our wonderful solar farm. 
BSR have demonstrated a commitment to achieving high standards of quality and value for money on many other solar farm sites." 
BSR describes itself as 'one of the leading providers of solar services in the UK'. 
Through a combination of hard work, technical know-how, professionalism and transparency, the firm says its 'dedicated and experienced team have been able to develop their offering to meet the requirements of both commercial and community projects alike'.

BOSTON (PRWEB) December 07, 2017 The Boston Center for Facial Rejuvenation is excited to announce that Leonard Miller, M.D. and Sean Doherty, M.D. have both been named as Top Docs for 2017 by Boston magazine. Dr. Miller and Dr. Doherty are honored to be ranked among the Top Docs in Boston magazine’s December issue. Once a year, Boston magazine puts together its much-anticipated listing of the area’s Top Docs. The physicians are chosen using an unbiased approach, through nominations from their colleagues and peers. Each Top Doc provides top-notch medical care, brings an exemplary bedside manner and maintains a flawless safety record. As two of this year’s Top Docs, Dr. Miller and Dr. Doherty offer their patients the full range of surgical and noninvasive aesthetic procedures for the face and body. Dr. Miller brings an innovative array of techniques for restoring and maintaining a refreshed, youthful face and neck. Addressing needs for the breast and body, Dr. Doherty’s customized treatment plans achieve sculpted, natural-looking curves and physical proportion. Dr. Miller is board certified by the American Board of Plastic Surgeons. With more than 25 years of plastic and cosmetic surgery experience, Dr. Miller is known for developing his own, cutting-edge noninvasive techniques for improving the appearance. These procedures, including ThermiTight and medical microneedling, can significantly postpone the need for surgical intervention. As founder of the Boston Center for Facial Rejuvenation , Dr. Miller is one of the most sought after cosmetic surgeons in New England. Dr. Doherty is a true humanist, striving to form a connection with each of his patients as a real person. Known for combining his artistic eye with innate technical precision, Dr. Doherty offers his patients the best in restorative techniques for the body, including breast augmentation, liposuction and gynecomastia correction. A graduate of Columbia University and Tufts University School of Medicine, Dr. Doherty is board certified by the American Board of Plastic Surgeons and routinely presents at conferences around the globe. For more information on the rejuvenating procedures offered at Boston Center for Facial Rejuvenation, contact the office at 617.735.8735 or send an email to robyn(at)leonardmillermd(dot)com. posts.title: Judge to begin charge to jury today Laura Babcock murder trial in Toronto
posts.text:
Posted Dec 7, 2017 4:00 am EST Last Updated Dec 7, 2017 at 4:40 am EST Laura Babcock is shown in a Toronto Police Service handout photo. THE CANADIAN PRESS/HO-Toronto Police Service MANDATORY CREDIT 
TORONTO – The judge at the trial of two men accused of killing a young Toronto woman five years ago and then burning her body is to begin his legal instructions to the jury today. 
Dellen Millard and Mark Smich have pleaded not guilty to first-degree murder in the presumed death of 23-year-old Laura Babcock. Babcock’s body has not been found. 
In its closing address on Wednesday the Crown said a “mountain” of circumstantial evidence points to Millard and Smich killing Babcock at Millard’s home some time after 8 p.m. on July 3, 2012 and then disposing of her body at Millard’s farm near Waterloo, Ont. 
The prosecution alleges Babcock was killed after becoming the odd woman out in a love triangle with Millard and his girlfriend. 
Smich’s lawyer told the jury on Wednesday that his client had no motive to kill Babcock because he was never part of a love triangle and all the Crown has is a rap song in which Smich says he killed a girl and burned her body. 
Millard, who represented himself, told the jury in his closing address Tuesday that several witnesses testified to having seen or heard from Babcock after July 4, 2012. Bitcoin Climbs Above $13,000 To Reach New All-Time High 
Bitcoin climbed above $13,000 Wednesday afternoon after topping $12,000 Tuesday night.
The digital currency began the year below $1,000 and its gains have accelerated as investor interest grows. Chicago-based Cboe Global Markets is planning to launch bitcoin futures on Sunday, while the world’s largest futures exchange, CME, is set to launch its futures product the following week. The addition of bitcoin futures by two respected exchanges marks another step towards establishing the digital currency as a legitimate asset class.
However, JPMorgan Chase Jamie Dimon has called bitcoin a “fraud.” Digital currency investor and former Fortress hedge fund manager Michael Novogratz also said last week that cryptocurrencies like bitcoin are “going to be the biggest bubble of our lifetimes.” Novogratz also predicted last week that bitcoin could reach $40,000 by the end of next year.
